  "datePublished": "2026-03-06",
  "description": "Syntax is the arrangement of words within sentences — the order, length, and structure of clauses. If diction is which words you choose, syntax is how you arrange them. Together they constitute prose style at the sentence level.\nShort sentences create urgency. Long sentences with nested clauses create complexity, delay, the feeling of a mind turning something over. A series of parallel clauses creates rhythm and emphasis. A sentence that withholds its main verb until the end creates suspense. These are syntactic effects — they work through structure, not vocabulary.\n",
